Four more ministers in the cabinet, total of sixty three
The four new federal ministers include two from the Mutahida Qaumi Movement and two from the Jamiat Ulamae Islam Fazalur Rehman Group.
President Asif Ali Zardari took the oath from the new ministers.
Prime Minister Yousuf Raza Gilani and members of cabinet were also present at the oath-taking ceremony.
After the inclusion of four new ministers to the federal cabinet, the number of federal ministers, state ministers, and advisers has reached a total of sixty-three.
Ministers Farooq Sattar and Babar Ghouri are from MQM, whereas Ministers Azam Swati and Molana Ataur Rehman are from the Jamiat Ulamae Islam Fazalur Rehman Group.
The departments of these ministers have not yet been announced.
Farooq Sattar is the convener of MQM, whereas Babar Ghouri is a senator from MQM whose term will expire on March 10.
Azam Swati was elected as a free senator and is considered to be one of the richest.
Moulana Ataur Rahman is a member of the National Assembly and is Moulana Fazlur Rahman's younger brother.
It should be remembered that four important officeholders are not members of the National Assembly.
It should be clear that on December 3, 2008, twenty-eight new ministers and eighteen ministers of state were taken into the cabinet. At that time it was believed that members of the MQM would also be included in the cabinet, but due to a difference in the distribution of ministries, MQM was not included.
Balochistan pipe line blown up.
According to the police, this was an eighteen inch wide pipe line that goes to the various wells in the gas plant of Peer mountain, and it was blown up by unidentified individuals in the morning.
Apart from this yesterday, well number three was destroyed in a blast and a gas pipe line was harmed by a blast near Allah Yaar Hill.
The responsibility for these blasts were claimed by the spokesperson for the banned organization, Baloch Republican Army: Sarbaz Baloch.
From the beginning of the year 2009, there was an increase in the number of extremist incidents.
In this month, there were dozens of incidents of gas pipes being blown up, and there were also an increase in attacks on trains and people from the state of Punjab.
Though the Chief Minister of Balochistan, Nawab Aslam Raeesani expressed distress over these incidents and the police were instructed to share information with intelligence agencies, but it was still not possible to stop these incidents.
